         <ref id="d2080e235a1310">
            <label>9</label>
            <mixed-citation id="d2080e242" publication-type="other">
A long and large book by Gerard de Cortanze, Philippe Sollers ou La volonté de bonheur,
roman (Paris: Éditions du Chêne, 2001), illustrates this difficulty perfectly. Written with
Sollers's cooperation, lavishly illustrated with authentic photographs, the book falls utterly
into the dichotomy of the collection it appears in: Vérité et légendes. What Sollers and others
(notably Dominique Rolin) are quoted as saying about his real life reveals almost nothing
new, whereas the author has recourse to Sollers's novels when he wants to go beyond such
common knowledge. Cortanze's subtitle ironically points to the book's ineffectual strategies:
La volonté de bonheur, roman.</mixed-citation>
